@theomancyCos @the_funhilde yeah i only started making them because i would get close to the end of a project and constantly forget i still had a bunch of small finishing tasks left. (this is how i ended putting on juri at katsu and discovered i never hemmed my pants 😭)

@theomancyCos @the_funhilde list making as an adhd-er is a delicate art, mine work as a “don’t forget steps” strategy rather than a “pick a step” strategy bc decision paralysis hits me hard. i hope you are able to find something that works, list or no.

@the_funhilde @theomancyCos alternatively i do a post it note list but each step gets one post it so when i finish i get to yank it off the wall. lists only work for me if they are both chaotic and tactile enough to be satisfying

@the_funhilde @theomancyCos yeah the only way lists work for me is if i make a massive list of every step i can possible do at a time and choose things to check off with all the grace of throwing a dart at it. when i was in school i’d do it on big poster boards and hang ‘em on the wall.

@this_chick25 of course! embroidery is fine everyone should try it out. :) having good tools and knowing what exists to help you is half the battle.

@tm_liza i had to google the character but that sounds super pretty!! a bunch of butterflies also definitely sounds like it'd be better as applique since you can make them all in one big frame. also you can totally make posable wings by couching thin wire around the edge of the wings.

@this_chick25 you should be able to gently tug on your thread without warping your fabric and not need to force it.
again, can't recommend hands-free hoops enough! this is the one i have. https://t.co/ZvfkrWHrvP

@this_chick25 also protect it a bit from the hoop warping it. your fabric should be taut enough that when you tap it it feels tight and bouncy. if you start to lose that tension, take the time to adjust it. waxed thread can help with this because it makes your thread slide smoothly.

@this_chick25 i do needle and thread as well! that sounds like an issue with fabric slipping out of your hoop. something you can do before you start embroidering is wrap your hoop (at least the internal one) with white or unbleached bias tape. this will make it hold your fabric stronger and

@this_chick25 overall it's something that takes patience and time, both to complete an individual project and to get good at. sit back, enjoy the process, and don't be too hard on yourself. you're not bad at it you're just still learning. :)

@this_chick25 i already know what i'm doing. then while i'm actually stitching, i don't try to rush, and i'm very careful about the placement of each stitch. i go back and pick things out if they aren't laying right. things like hands free hoop stands and a good light will also help with that.

@this_chick25 can you be more specific about the tension issue you're having?
as for knowing where to sew, that comes down to planning and control. i actually sketch out all my embroidery, using pencil strokes to represent how my stitches/beads/metal will lay, so by the time i get to thread
@tm_liza i definitely prefer applique to embroidery directly! more control, less nerve wracking, can be removable for transit/washing. what's the big project? 👀
